Re-calibrated level.
Unclogged sediment resting on top of sensor by sawing and then putting back together PVC.
Installed new pH sensor. Moved sensors so turbidity and conductivity were adjacent. Sensor now lies ~0.5 feet further above the channel bed due to sediment inundation.
Black water event occuring early in the week; still highly turbid water. Sensor dirty, wiper unable to clear most sediment off.
Cleaned sonde - it was super dirty, didn't bring laptop so I'll go back for the photos
Cleaned sonde and changed out batteries. River looking N A S T Y.

photos_downloaded: Yes, camera stopped at 8/8 for some reason? It was on "On", so I switched it to "Setup"...
visit_comments: Cleaned sonde, checked data as specific conductivity (or actual) wasn't reading. On live reading, conductivity was fine but pH was not read. Removed then reinstalled pH sensor fixed it. Downloaded photos.
Cleaned sensors, checked camera - it is still not taking any new pictures... sonde and housing were dirty so we cleaned it
Began calibrating and cleaning sensors, and AquaTroll stopped responding. Turned off log and placed sensor in calibration mode with water to be checked later

photos_downloaded: field pic taken, camera not functioning
visit_comments: VuLink was not recognizing sensor; I disconnected both cable junctions and cleaned them as well as the sensor junction. VuLink then recognized sensor upon reconnection. Checked camera and it wasn't taking pictures even though it was on "on" and had a SIM card. Deleted old pics. Will return to check and clean stuff. Checked outfalls upstream and downstream of sensor and discovered a small stream coming from somewhere east of the Archery Range, going under the Archery Range road, then emptying downstream from sonde onto hillside and into river. We should look into this outfall and the one under the bridge. Took pictures of that stuff.

Cleaned sonde. VuLink once again did not recognize AT. Could still be a cord issue. Cleaned cord again with brush and reconnected. Perhaps this could be an issue with the log as well, where each time you connect the cord/VuLink doesn't like that a log is going? Because every time I stop the log, it connects successfully (could be coincidental). Checked and pulled camera as it was not taking pictures. Got error message that VuLink was not connected to server but I sent a Test Upload and it worked.
Pulled sensor. River very low. Left bank still very wet. Not sure if we downloaded the data or not so we will need to check this.

Installed sonde and VuLink. Flows very low and considerable algae buildup at base of PVC underwater. Water moving so slowly that winds were blowing surface of water backwards, creating a CCW current under and north of the bridge which dammed a lot of algae and gunk against the debris/muskrat peninsula. Well dock LACKS SMALLER SECONDARY RING: WILL RETURN TO ADD IT/ANCHOR IN ANOTHER WAY
Downloaded data. Installed field camera.
Replaced AT 500 with the beta AT 800.
Cleaned sonde and started new log. Replaced camera SD card. AT800 looks good.

Stage high. Calibrated; had to use a lot of cal fluid. InSitu phone is not on a cellular network, so I had to email the data and cal report to myself by setting up a mobile hotspot with my phone. Changed upload frequency to 6hr at end of VuSitu connection.
Cleaned sensors. Not sure why turbidity drops to 0 at times. Logging on both VuLink and AT800
Cleaned housing and Sonde, Some sediment on sensors. Could not check live readings. Cap seems to be cross threaded and will need to be fixed.

Cleaned. Sediment and gunk is getting in resistor cap threads making it hard to unscrew, so I wiped it out. Might be a design flaw. Turbidity sometimes 0 on Live Readings and log but okay/better overall on log and after cleaning.

Cleaned. Turbidity is either 0 or 500NTU in live reading and 0 on log. Chl-a also read errors on Live Reading, so I switched them but error persisted. Added more grease and switched back but error still persisted. Eventually turbidity showed 10NTU on log, which seems too low. Chl-a started reading consistent values. Flows pretty high.

photos_downloaded: No, SD card needs checked soon
visit_comments: Swapped AT800 and VuLink out and replaced with AT500 (SN 667320) and Tamasag's old VuLink (SN 1011876). Calibrated AT500 including level. Water depth and discharge super high. Weird hillside no longer weeping... maybe construction is moving away? AT800 issues: pH not logging  and turbidity sometimes 0 sometimes also not logging... Test upload with Tamasag VuLink failed
Switched Tamasag VuLink (SN 1011876) with spare VuLink in my car (SN 821962), so now data from Archery should show up on HydroVu.
live readings looked good besides depth, but the preview depth was good. Said RDO cap might be expired, but it looked good.

VuLink Battery was at 36%. Flows were high, water level seemed higher than last time I was there (2023-06-06). Live readings loked good. I took a couple of twigs and other debrees out of the sensor. Collected the SD card and replaced it with a new one. Taped the new projecr sign on the top of the camera. Cleaned housing

Downloaded the new software update for the VuLink, Changed the SD card for the camera, battery level for the camera was at 65%. Put new batteries in the VuLink battery is at 99%. Calibrations & live readings looked good. Cleaned the housing and callibrated the AT. RDO callibrated well and looked good, however I got a notifcation that the RDO cap was expired and should be replaced.

photos_downloaded: Sd card collected and field pics taken
visit_comments: I couldn’t connect to the VuLink at first, I had to change the batteries and than I was able to connect. Live readings looked good, I pulled the AT out of the water and it looked fairly clean. Next, I cleaned off the sensors and deleted the old logs, and started a new log. Water levels were lower than the last time I was there, sonde depth came in at 2 feet after I redeployed it. Swapped SD cards camera battery was at 38%.

sensor_malfunction: Vu link not logging or uploading

crew: Sam Struthers, Juan De La Torre
visit_comments: Pulled sensor, very dirty from recent storms and some biofilm on exterior of sonde. Cleaned up nicely, calibrated well, RDO Cap expiration warning but calibrated quickly. Live readings looked good after deployment (higher DO after cleaning), taped up cable to shorten, locked up and left. Juan checked on camera, batteries where dead and there were only 5 pictures when I downloaded them, swapped in new batteries and SD card.

Swapped the lock on top of housing for masterlock, live readings looked good upon arival. Sonde had slight levels off sediment/film on the sensors. Performed calibrations on RDO, Conductivity,pH,ORP. Swapped SD card and replaced camera bateries.

Connected cu at500 with splitter and redeployed with them stacked atop one other (CU higher), CSU depth was 2.2 ft, CU at .5. should swap to 4 in when I'm back from reno. Should also make the sondes sit higher in water column, chla was very different between the two sondes (maybe balance the two in QA)
Checked site due to log stopping. Attempted to fix but could not fix.
Replaced broken VuLink with a functioning one.
calibrated our sonde, sensors had slight levels biofilm on them. I rinsed off the cu sonde but didn't do a deep clean.

sensor_malfunction: Not realy a malfunction RDO cap is said to be expired sn 679525, however no problem while calibrating
visit_comments: Upgraded vulink to v1.76. Turbidty was 0 ntu for CU sonde when I checked live readings. Cleaned CU sonde was not to dirty for not being cleaned for a little while. Downloaded log from vulink deselected TDS, resisitivity,pressure,salinity,density, and extrernal voltage for CU sonde. Swapped SD cards for camera, due to lack of batteries I got the camerra to about 40% battery, when we get more 3a I will replace them to get it to 100%
pH calibrated

Deployed CU AT500 and RDO blue, tried to zip tie together but was barely too small to fit down 3 in pipe, sent them down separately then kat pulled the RDO blue down as low as it could go. Temps between instruments were pretty close but off by .5-1C. Can use temp as QA until we make pipe big enough to fit both nicely
vulink wasn't uploading data, i downloaded the log and started a new one, did a test upload and the comunication issue resolvled it self.

cleaned CU sonde and rdo probe. I pulled the rdo probe and swapped the connection from the splitter directly between vulink and aqua troll. brought the splitter and rdo probe back to the lab waiting for renovation to make them fit better in housing.

crew: Sam Struthers, Juan De La Torre
visit_comments: Added new pipe and redeployed AT500 and RDO Blue. RDO blue in 3 in pipe with vulink and at500 in 2 in pipe. removed random t posts and sat 2 in pipe slightly higher in water column to avoid sedimentation. Depth decreased by .1 from start to finish

vulink wouldn't turn on when it i tried to check live readings in housing. I pulled the vulink, RDO probe and AT out of housing, the vulink worked after that... Swapped the vulink for anoter one, had to update the firmware on the new vulink. I could not get the AT back in the housing, had to pull set up and bring it home for the night will redploy it tommorow 2023-10-24. downloaded the log and changed wiper to activate wiper every reading.

Tried getting the AT into the smaller housing kept gettinf stuck halfway down. Removed splitter connected vulink to AT directly and redployed in original housing. changed wiper frequency to activate before every reading. started a new log. brought the old vulink and rdo probe back to nesb. new vulink at site serial number:  814154
Deployed sonde at new installation at Boxelder Sanitation. pH sensor replaced with new one.
Calibrated, moved camera and downloaded pictures, reinforced PVC.
Black water event occuring early in the week; still extremely turbid water. Sensor dirty but wiper managed to clear most debris off.
Cleaned all sensors and wiper as they had a lot of mud and some weird tubule things were growing in the resistor. Calibrated turbidity
Cleaned sonde, river velocity is very low, calibrated turbidity on 8/30
Cleaned sonde, brushed muck off of housing
Cleaned sensor, checked data, connected spare sensor with functional turbidity to VuLink and pulled sensor with bad turbidity, accidentally disconnected antenna wire on VuLink then reconnected it
Sent Test Upload because I thought VuLink wasn't uploading data, but it actually was and wast just named "Rist", downloaded files starting at 9/14 since they didn't send to my email last time
ELC looked good. Calibrated all sensors but RDO. Water relatively clear, but sensors needed cleaning (guessing the rain last weekend brought in some heavier sediment loads).

photos_downloaded: Yes, camera stopped taking pictures on 10/15 but seemed to be working?
visit_comments: Replaced AT and VuLink batteries. AT battery level did not update after battery replacement and still has not updated. Cleaned sonde and downloaded photos. Stage and Q are very very low.

River stage and volume very high. Light leaf litter concentrations floating both on surface and below 1m deep. Replaced AT600 batteries and its battery is still reading too low (25%) as I used new batteries. Needs to be checked again.
Pulled sensor, River very low. River was beginning to freeze in shaded pools.
Sonde deployed

Installed camera. Cleaned sonde and replaced sonde (AT 600) batteries. Even after replacing batteries, AT600 still saying 0% battery. This might be a glitch we need to tell In-Situ about. Saw several fish and angled camera down towards river with door stop.

Battery still saying 0% on AT600. Calibrated and cleaned sonde. Strapped PCV to stairs near water with black rubber strap with a QuickLink to make it reach all the way. Low flow with two fish jumps. Lots of algae/nasty stuff on water surface in still areas

photos_downloaded: No, will come back to collect SD card
visit_comments: Cleaned. Water very turbid, murky, chocolate water. Lots of suspended sediment and some LWD. Replaced VuLink and sonde batteries with sonde still reporting 0% even with fresh batteries.

photos_downloaded: Yes, SD card collected and replaced
visit_comments: Battery still messed up on AT600: remains 0% even after disconnecting from both sonde and VuLink and waiting before installing batteries. Calibrated. Water depth and discharge high with turbidity reading 50NTU. Had to factory reset sonde after calling In-Situ because memory was full, causing conductivity calibration to fail while cal report was being generated >:/ Replaced camera SD and batteries.

Live readings looked good initially, the depth was 8.24ft! Super clean Sonde, troll battery doesn't work still. 10NTU read 5. Camera face planted into the ground, so we reattached to pole. Some of the temps were not stable when accepting calibrations

VuLink Batterry was at 62%, I cleaned the sensor it had a small amount of sediment on it, after this the live readings improved and looked accurate. depth was 7.33 feet when I deployed AT and turbidity was in the 70s. I collected the SD card and replaced it with a new one, there was no need to add sign because there was one already right by the camera. Cleaned housing

Turbidity was very high on hydroVu. sonde was reading 80NTU at arrival and had some but not much sediment build up. cleaned sonde and tested in tap water (recorded 3-5 NTU), wiper was a bit worn so i replaced it with a new one. redeployed sonde and was now recording 14-18NTU. re started log, sent test upload and disconnected.

Updated software, but needed to disconnect and reconnect to get the blue "paused" bar. Live readigns: depth 5.3ft, RDO low (4, 46%), and turb high (200ish). Pretty clean, little sediment. Temp wouldn't stabilize on pH7 and RDO. Perhaps pH7 temp didn't stabilize (nomial) because it was super hot out. Same prob w pH10 but it fixed itself in the shade. Cleaned housing, and brought sonde up 1.3ft w black duct tape.

HydroVu data was looking wonky. The numbers were fluctuating significantly within one day. Turbidity was reading numbers in the 700NTU range, and RDO hung around 50% and less than 4mg/L. This all seemed odd considering Jed and I calibrated yesterday. The live readings were all good upon site arrival, and the Sonde had very little sediment on only a fraction of the cap. Moved the Sonde up to 2.6ft with gray tape. I dug around the PVC trying to clear out excess sediment, but it didn't seem like there was that much. It was quite difficult to reach, however, and so my cleaning was likely not the most efficient. I believe a hook would be helpful to get around the stairs under the pipe fully.

photos_downloaded: Sd card collected and field pics taken
visit_comments: Mild sediment on sensors, after I cleaned the housing the brush got stuck in the housing I had to cut the top of the PVC inorder to get it out I retapped it on, we should glue it. The bottom of the housing is buried in sediment in the bottom of the river. the AT was in the water however, not touching the sediment. Water levels are significantly lower than last time I was there, lots of bottom of the river are exposed. Calibrated the sonde and live readings looked good, however conductivity was higher than it has been reading 587.05 micro S/cm. Lastly I swapped out the SD cards and put new batteries in the camera. Camera battery was at 0% uppon arrival may have some missing fotos due this.

tried to solve sediment issues, moved some sediment near the housing, will need to dig out channel to ensure flow is more concentrated at sonde. deployed at .8 ft up from 1.04 ft. reset camera to reduce pictures taken

vu link was uploading data correctly but would not connect via vu situ or turn on. tried batteries, did not work. replaced with rental 926189-23215. connected just fine then. cleaned and checked live readings. removed cap to allow Sediment to pass thru.

Sonde was not submerged (cable wasn't suspended long enough). Is now submerged. Added additional bracket to bottom end of PVC.

turbidity data was slightly weird (flashy, above 50NTU at times) prior to visit. Calibrated turbidity. Retaped cord as it was potentially getting sonde above water level. Sonde was quite gunky for this time of year and flows were pretty high (200cfs)
Added well dock. Did not pull VuLink up more than about 1"
Q and stage getting higher here. Sonde and wiper a bit dirty. Branches and woody debris stuck on PVC and in gap between it and concrete bridge support
Cleaned sonde. Everything looks good.
Cleaned and downloaded data. Flows and stage increasing.
Calibrations were in the desired ranges. Live readings looked good. Turbity was in the 180s, depth was 2,3 feet. Minimal sensor sediment. High flows water very turbid.  Couldn’t access sd card.
Stoppped by to show FCGOV folks the sensor and cleaned it out. Some small debris in the sensor but overall quite clean.

Live readings for depth were negative, but preview was good, turb readings were too high at 100NTU. It wasn't caked in sediment, but it was grimy around the restrictor interior and in the brush. RDO cap is expired, but looked good.RDO temp would not stabilize, so calibrated at nominal (which according to InSitu via phone call is just the Sonde being old). Sonde was diconnected and then reconnected and unpaused, but I don't think it left the water when unpaused. VuLink wouldn't turn on, so I replaced the batteries with new ones (even though the old ones were 79% -- these batteries are in the new batteries box). This fixed the problem. Camera SD card was replaced as well. Flows were high.

came to check on logging issue. log was started when i got there but only 2 data points existed. created a new log at 15 min and 30 min upload. cleared all old logs. will update online to 6hr upload when data has been properly coming in.
Legacy was still set to upload at 30 min, updated to 3 hours. cleaned sonde with tap and DI water. restarted log, sent test upload and disconnected
Went to Legacy just to do the software update…ideally will save 20 min for the next visit. Live readings did look good, and I did need to disconnect to see the blue "paused bar"

rdo_cap_condition: Fair (white speckles are starting to go away)
photos_downloaded: SD card collected and field pictures
visit_comments: live readings good, cleaned some gunk off but mostly clean, calibrated smoothly. got warning that RDO cap is expired. live readings with deployment looked good.

crew: Chloe Miller, Juan De La Torre
visit_comments: Pre live: RDO (90%), turb (30ntu) -- not that murky. Thin layer of sediment on sensors and inside restrictor. O ring under sensors was broken (snapped off) causing liquid to just fall right through the bottom holes when the sonde is in calibration mode. We fixed this problem to calibrate by pulling the O ring tightly and then duct taping it...this worked well enough to calibrate all of them (conductivity did get a little water in the port plug (don't think that was from the lack of o ring though) but it fixed itself once dried off (restored calib defaults in the process). Catalina helped O ring size (Chloe has sizing email). SD card changed. RDO past its lifetime, but cap looked good. 10 NTU read 3, 100 read 85. Batteries were at 30%, but as soon as we changed batteries to the big gray ones, the lights wouldn't turn on. uhg.
Cleaned sensor and its housing. Turbidity was unreasonably high - recalibrated and it was fine.
swapped the turbidty sensor water levels were low live readings looked good

crew: Juan De La Torre, Sam Struthers
visit_comments: Site visit to switch pvc housing from 2" to 4" pipe. Stopped log when we arrived and restarted log when we were finished. Sonde was left in river while the housing was being switched.

Pre live said RDO was 10.4 and 106%...turb was 15NTU. Depth at 1ft. Sonde had ver little sediment, but the brush had some sedmement in the bristles (not on the sensors). RDO cap expired, but looks good. No microfiber cloth so used my shirt. Turb 10NTU read 15, and 100NTU read 109 during calibration. Post live, RDO was still super high at 9.85 and 125%, and turbidity read 0...which was definitely not the case. Depth at .9ft. Changed SD card. Saw horses walk through Poudre.
Swapped tube batteries. Alkaline batteries should not be used in the future. (i.e., Lithium only)

Camera batteries good, SD card replaced, time changed to be correct. The sonde was a mess, went to fix the issue where turb = 0, and RDO not showing up on HydroVu. Sonde was saying that RDO and conductivity sensors weren't even inside of the sensor ports, so I went to fix that by taking them out and putting them back in (greased). John had me reset the factory settings on the VuLink, but afterwards the VuLink and AT wouldn't connect to one another. VuLink would also not turn off on its own after I disconnected. Pulled sonde and stored w pH4 solution.
Cleared existing logs after deploying, started new log, test upload worked.

This site went super well! Turb was reading low numbers in the pre live (around .6NTU), but the water and sonder were both quite clear. pH in pre live was about 9. Depth isn't read on this sonde, but the water is getting quite low there, about only half of the restrictor was covered. Wiper is working well, the biofilm was only on the wiper and not the sensors! Added a new SD card, but camera batteries are still kicking it at 3/4. Post live turb was 3NTU, and pH was 8.14.

Cleaned sonde, besides that everthing looked good values stayed similair post cleaining on live readings. Vulink was not connected properly to housing top, fixed before I left after a little mishap. downloaded the vulink log

Sonde not showing up on HydroVu after access granted by In-Situ. Connected to VuLink and downloaded log. VuLink said "Connected Pulse Instrument" in Connected Instruments. We couldn't access/do anything with the Pulse instrument. Upon first connection, I did see an AT with a serial number starting with 4, but it never showed up after that. VuLink log also only had pressure, T, acre feet, battery, and datetime. We did NOT remove the AT because the cord was carefully folded and we did not want to mess it up. We did not find a solution to the AT600 not showing up...
pulled sonde and pipe, sonde was dry when removed and had significant sediment built up. returned pipe to in situ and sonde to NESB

crew: Chloe Miller, Sam Struthers, Jed Lichtensztajn
visit_comments: Changed housing set up so that the sonde sat at a deeper part of the river by shifting the housing up stream, and moving some of the brackets north as well. May need to come back to install something that will dampen force of the river as it hits the housing's side. Square angular posts?

Also not uploading to HydroVu, fixed by just checking on sonde and doing a 5 min uploading interval to make sure data was ocming in. Test upload worked. Jed pulled 2 large sticks that were caught outside of the housing.
Cleaned sensor and housing. Swapped 15 ft. cable for 25 ft. rental cable.

Showed up connected to Vulink and checked live readins on AT however lost comunication with it was on the phone for a hour and a half pulled the AT and Vulink and brought it back to the lab the conecting cable 25ft was faulty

Had troubles getting it to the bottom of the housing, had to cut a new hole in the pipe to help it down. Needed speed to break thru pvc glue. Started new log, forgot to reset upload to 3 hour vs 1 day.
Changed upload time from 1 day to 3 hours

sensor_swapped_notes: Swapped boxelder turb for lincoln turb
sensor_malfunction: Turbdity not logging correctly, swapped sensors
visit_comments: Turbidity hasn't been sending data to hydrovu it has been flatlined on 0 since 700 deployment. I callibrated Turbdiity the 10 ntu calllibration was jumping all ovef the place, however eventually got it to stabalize around 8 ntu. called tech support and send John from insitu the Vulink Log he said he will get back to me. On live readings I could see that the troll was reading Turbidty at around 7 ntu.

Upgraded VuLink firmware. Water levels were super low. Not super dirty, but some biofilm present. Live readings for RDO were around 9 and 123%. Depth at .1ft. Calibrations went well, needed to restore calib defaults for RDO because there was an error in calibration. RDO cap looked like its on its way out, will likely make it until the end of the season. Placed the sonde back in as far as it could go (depth still at .1ft). Live readings looked good, RDO still around 120%. Turb went from 50 pre live to 5 post live!

rdo_cap_condition: White speckles were faded and smaller

Battery was at 33%, I chose to leave it but may need to return soon. Said 64 days of life left but idk how accurate those are.

Checked on Sonde live readings looksed good and matched the probe. Turbidity however, was too high at like 180. Checked on Sonde, and there was sediment caked only on the cap, not the sensors. Rob Graves didn't like that we were there :')

crew: Chloe Miller, Jed Lichtensztajn, Sam Struthers
visit_comments: Installed the new sonde at PBD location, which had pre-existing housing. we cleaned the housing which had a layer of sediment towards the bottom of the sonde preventing the AT from reaching a desired depth. We deployed the new sonde and noticed that the RDO sat % was pretty low reading mid 70s so we callibrated it and than it was reading mid 80s for RDO sat % and mid 8s mg/L. additionally we bolted the sonde the cement to prevent it from falling in the river. there is no signal out there so we couldn't send a test upload. We will need to keep an eye on this sonde to make sure everything is working properly.

Most data looked good, however turbidity was extremly high in the mid 1000s, due to the fact that the ristricitor cap was filled up completly with sediment. I cleaned the housing, and downloaded the log. The rest of the live readings looked good after cleaninig the sediment out. Therefore I did not calibrate

crew: Chloe Miller, Sam Struthers, Jed Lichtensztajn

Pulled housing out, drilled holes and removed cap on bottom. Added additional bracket for high flows. Redeployed sensor and disconnected.

crew: Chloe Miller, Sam Struthers, Jed Lichtensztajn

calibrated all the sensors except turbidity it was reading the standers completly off! 10 NTU standerd was reading in the 1000s, I suspect the turbidity for the 700 is not as sensitve to lower NTU's. kept it at facotry defaults need to look into this turbidty calibration issue. water levels were significanlty lower only about half a foot deep at housing.

Downloaded log 9/19-9/21, live values looked good, some gunk on sensors but nothing crazy. Put on high gain antenna and test upload went thru, it is a CU vulink so I cannot see if it is properly uploading

visit_comments: Connnection and test upload good with new antenna, cleaned gunk off  wiper and sensors with cloth. New log, depth same as on arrival. Disconnect 16:05 mdt

Live readings looked normal except for a 30NTU reading. Fine sediment layer on the sensors, and the wiper highkey was not doing anything to help that problem (mangled, and wasn't touching the sensor). So we replaced it with a brand new wiper! Just cleaned. Post live looked good at 5NTU.

Changed SD card, batteries were at full power. Live readings on the Sonde were high for conductivity (570), but everything else looked good (depth at 1.33 ft). Very little sediment on the sonde. Sonde disconnected from hydrovu as pH was calbirating so I had to restart. Post live readings looked good, (conductivity still at 590). RDO saturation was at 109%. Is that too high? End depth at 1.25ft.

Live readings looked good, cleaned the sensors and changed the batteries for the VuLink. The wiper was acting funny it would work as it usual does and after a couple rotations it would get caught and make clicking noises. I swapped the wiper and same problem pressited. The sensor were not very dirty upoono arrival however we should keep an eye on this.

Changed lock, checked on VuLink issue where the VuLink stops uploading to hydrovu randomly. Andy from InSitu said that it was just a problem with out cell service. Changed uploading to 5 minutes until the VuLink worked, downloaded both data logs, and changed back to 3 hour uploading rate.

Turbidity was pretty high at 100NTU (post storm). Sonde was a litle gunky, not caked…mostly soft sediment. Cleaned sonde and then post live readings looked good with turb back down to 30. Test upload good.

Went to site to calibrate and upgrade housing to 4 in pipe. Pulled sensor at 9:30MDT, kept in tap water while working on housing, calibrated just fine. Housing had some damage on lower brackets, tried to attach a new one at the bottom, will check on later. Redeployed using new well cap and housing.

Cleaned sonde, turbidity was fluctuating greatly in live readings (16-80NTU). Other live readings looked okay. Depth 1.93ft. Sonde was nasty w what I assume was biofilm, came right off with microfiber cloth, but wouldn't rinse off with water. Post live readings were good, although turb was 2 which seemed too low for the state of the river (sun was going down though so it was in the shade).

Pre live turb was pretty high (30-50), there was a lot of biofilm on there (although to be expected). Depth 2.14ft. RDO error after in calibration stage, but after restoring calib defaults it was okay. Post live turb was around 10NTU, depth went down to 1.62ft. Started 2 new logs (bc of restoring calib defaults) and wiper was set to 30 min instead of an hour to reduce biofilm, hopefully. Changed SD card, dropped the door stop in the water...

sensor_malfunction: Vulink had temp of 0…maybe overheating issue
visit_comments: Connected cu at500 with splitter and redeployed with them connected together, Vulink had temp of 0…maybe overheating issue, battery was at 38% and then tanked to 25% after first upload. Still uploading fine just decreasing faster

Poured water into restrictor (sondes looked pretty clean) but I couldn't take the sondes apart in order to get the restrictor off because the zip tie was pretty snug on there. Changed batteries to new fancy lithium ones, but afterwards when my phone reconnected to the sonde it wouldn't go past the syncronizing screen (so I skipped like at PBD) to start the log up again. Took me forever to get the cap back on, but it's because the rubber on the outside has expanded to past the lip of the green thing so it looks like the green thing should be entirely inside of the rubber.

sensor_malfunction: RDO -- from 2018 -- won't talk to cap
visit_comments: Sondes were both super caked in biofilm, depth around 1.6 ft. RDO was through the roof at around 13 and 170%, which might be telling of the proceeding issues. Otherwise turb was fairly high at around 50NTU. For calibrating, RDO read an error after successfully calibrating (which happened last time I was there) so I stopped the logs and restored calib defaults for RDO. Solved problem, except temperature would not stabilize (RDO did, however), and was taking an incredibly long time to read RDO. Had to restore calib defaults for conductivity, too, because it would go from yellow to red a bunch of times (once I did it fixed itself). Everything else went well. The sonde eventually started to tell me that RDO cap was not installed, tried switching caps, didn't work. InSitu said to change the sensor itself as it is likely having problems connecting to the circut under the cap. Tried grease as well, but when you go to live readings, there's just a red triangle (warning) for RDO. I set a test upload, and RDO data did not come through. Changed camera SD card, batteries were at 3/4, didn't change them. Camera was facing a bit to the west. Cleaned CU sonde too.
solved RDO sensor issue from previous day, downloaded all logs, swapped sensors,  live readings looked good, started new logs. Disconnected at 945 mdt

Went to prospect to clean turbidity sensor, it was showing strange data on hydrovu, I cleaned it and has been reading better now. I also calibrated RDO saturation and got an error so I performed a hardware reset on the AT I downladed all the log on our AT and vulink log. Lastly I started a new log on the AT and vulink.

The camera and everything that came with it was gone. Pre live readings were good, RDO was at 11 and 134%, thoug. Depth at 1.38ft. Wiper working on our sonde ASTONISHINGLY well, it was caked with biofilm (as was the restrictor, but our sensors were doing great and super clean! CU sonde was grimy, but looked as if it wasn't even touching the sensor. RDO temp wouldn't stabilize, waited so long that RDO unstabilized, but when I finally went through with the calibration, it gave me an error that I have recieved the past two times I have been there: MEMORY CARD FULL. So, I restored calib defaults for RDO and it worked like a charm. Turb calib went well, but couldn't detect 10NTU and read 6.8 instead. Post live were good, RDO went down to 8.8 and about 119%. Started two new logs and cleaned CU sonde.

HIGH turbidity with restrictor being clogged with sediment so much that wiper was not turning and sensors were covered. Removed sediment and cleaned sensors. Q and depth too high for me to access bottom of PVC, so now sonde is at ~2ft when it was ~3ft before.
Tried to clean inside PVC with Sam Extendable Brush but it wouldn't reach all the way down - too short. Brushed outside and got sonde to same depth it was on 05/08 (~2ft).

Cleaned housing and sonde. Sediment on one half of sensors. Removed woody debris from housing and flushed housing of sediment. Level was off for live readings, recalibrated, live readings were correct then deployed. Shortened cable by 5-10 inches to try to avoid sedimentation
Cleaned cause RDO was noisy and falling to 0 but sonde not *that* dirty? Got sonde down to 2.62ft. Thunderstorm with 20min of heavy rain occurred while I was there.

Sonde began sending data on HydroVu

Flows were high and water was turbid. Pulled sensor up a bit. Turbidity sensor was off by 5 in 10NTU and 50 in 100 NTU

Top of sonde, part of cable, and sensors CAKED with mud so I cleaned it. Cleaned some sediment out of PVC with Sam brush. Disconnected from both devices and waited before installing two different kinds of fresh batteries but sonde reported 27% (same percentage as before uh oh). Upon redeployment, depth was 1.7ft so I think I got it deeper and turbidity was 42NTU. Water definitely clearer today than most of this month.

Sensor was CAKED in dirt, so a lot of the initial live readings were a little off (such as RDO saturation being 70-80%). We got an error calculating DO, but fixed it by restoring calibration default. Batteries were replaced. AquaTroll would keep unpausing after we restarted the app to troubleshoot for RDO. Turbidity calculations were quite off, 10 NTU read aroudn 20, and 100 NTU read around 200. Live readings looked good after calibrations. New logs were started on both VuLink and AquaTroll.

Just cleaned the Sonde, turbidity and DO were way off near 0, but post cleaning they were back to normal. After placing back into water, the depth was .25 ft (it didn't seem like the Sonde could be pushed any further. I added duct tape to the coil.) Sattellite was tucked into tube and live reading worked! Batteries were switched out on the camera.

Live readings looked okay, but depth was quite low .32 feet. I realized that the Sonde got stuck in the PVC so I shook it as much as I could, and then it would keep sliding. However, the depth would not increase at all. 10 NtU read 3, and 100 read 130ish. RESTRICTOR CAP REMOVED. SD card replaced. Calibrations went smoothly (yay!).

Aqua Troll was not submerged in water when I arrived, this explains the irregular depth reading and other data. Once the troll was out of the housing I could see it was filled almost to the brim with sediment. After cleaning the AT I replaced the turbidity sensor with a new one, the old serial number for the sensor is 1006140. Lastly, I cleaned the housing with the brush in order to get the AT to sit at the proper location within the housing. The depth read 1.5 feet after all was done. VuLink battery was at 34%, AT battery at 57%

Downloaded the new software update for the VuLink, AT was completely filled with sediment, which explains the irregular data. I cleaned the AT and housing, Water levels are lower and turbidity fluctuated between 3-8. I removed the cap for the AT. Depth of AT was 1.05 feet after I redployed it

HydroVu was blowing up our phone, so we went and changed the batteries (now near 100%). A little grimy on the sensors, and the cap is off!! Live turbidity was 121, and cleaning it only made it go down to 100 or so.

Pre live readings good (cond = 65, turb = 27, depth = .34 ft). It was CAKED in soft sediment that washed away easily. I forgot to pause the troll log until first calibration. All tape is now off of the cord, and the sonde sits at .97ft when I left. pH and ORP WERE NOT CALIBRATED because according to InSitu there needs to be more pH reference solution. I added more grease and restored calib defaults (and started two new logs respectively), but neither worked. pH read 8.3 in the post live readings though. I rinsed out the housing with river water and that seemed to help quite a bit, but after putting it in the first time the sonde was still reading high Ntu so I pulled it out again where I saw sediment build up already. I rinsed a second time, and post live readings said around 4-8NTU. Changed SD card only.

Data looked good on live readings and logs. However I went to Tamasag to fix the issues with the data not being sent to to hydrovu.. The connection went dark on the 20th of July. I callled Insitu and they suggested switching antennas. I couldn't synchronize was waiting for close to an hour. eventualy skipped synchorization and was able to download the logs. cleaned the housing with brush

crew: Chloe Miller, Juan De La Torre

I used the small flat head screwdriver to get rid of any air bubbles by pushing down into the junction solution hole. I previously restored calib defualts and dried out the wiper port (and regreased), but after I added more ref solution, it let me calibrate. Turb post calibrations read 1.66 which seems way too low. Depth at .26ft, although sonde wasn't pushed all the way in yet. Tried new antenna, doesn't work (light was still red, and the test upload was not doing anything). 2 new logs started. Changed SD card and batteries although batteries would only go up to 76% after changing a few of them. Got a paper napkin note saying I was trespassing haha.

Looks good, flow a little higher
Downloaded old 2022 data, checked camera and camera is maybe messed up
Cleaned sensor (very dirty) and housing. Cleaning seemed to disrupt ORP readings? Also do not think sensor was placed at bottom of PVC.
Calibrated pH and ORP,  removed camera
Checked and cleaned sensor after heavy rains - noticed buildup of sand on wiper and in restrictor holes
Swapped VuLink batteries. Evidence of storm event = chocolate milk water!
Calibrated turbidity

Installed new pH sensor. Moved sensors so turbidity and conductivity were adjacent. Shortened cable for sensor to now lie ~0.5 feet further above the channel bed due to sediment inundation; previously only one inch above bed. Turbidity data not loading to HydroVu.
Downloaded data
Checked and cleaned sensor and wiper
Black water event occuring early in the week; still chocolate milk water. Sensor dirty but wiper managed to clear most debris off.
Cleaned all sensors and wiper due to sediment buildup.
Sonde was super dirty so replaced wiper, calibrated everything nicely. Watch the batteries; might need replacement in 1-3 weeks

Cleaned sonde, set turbidity to factory cal defaults (seemed way to high; water quite clear). Believe issue may be that sensor was suspended over roots that have grown in. Dropped sensor to be a little lower in channel to avoid roots.
Life check because I forgot that you already replaced batteries. River seems a lot higher than it has been lately; checked USGS and that agrees with what I saw (30-40cfs), 0.8ft gauge height
Cleaned sensors, cleaned housing - lots of algae
All sensors were cleaned and all but RDO were calibrated. Flow was low, but moving.
Cleaned sonde and housing.

Stage and volumne high. Saw beaver on east side of path that had just brought down a tree. Took pictures of beaver and sensor surroundings. Need to watch out for beavers upstream of sensor again. Bank has been eroded more upstream from sensor.

River super low; sonde had mud caked on it and seemed barely wet when I pulled it out. Conductivity sensor didn't look that bad. Calibrated conductivity as actual&specific conductivity, TDS, resistivity, salinity, and density were all way too wavy. Calibration fixed these issues. It looks like the sonde was not at the end of the tube because depth increased right after I reinstalled it and gauge height/q didn't change.
Pulled sensor. River very low. Beaver activity still ongoing.
Installed sonde and VuLink. Widespread beaver activity now on sensor (W) side of river. Folded cable so it would fit. Flows very low.
Could not connect to VuLink. Sensor housing broken; must return to fix.

Deployed sonde then pulled the cord and secured it so that the sonde didn't feel like it was hitting the end. Water a bit too deep and fast for me to check comfortably. Water depth and streamfow quite high. Moved camera box lock to Grip 'n Lock cap and put new lock (combo 718) on camera box. Added little identifier sign to camera box.

Turbidity was high (99NTU) and sensors were dirty because wiper was not installed correctly. Wiper had not been screwed in at the gap, so the brush was a few mm short of the sensors and not making contact with them. Fixed wiper and cleaned sensors.

Cleaned sensors. Flows super high, channel geometry and geomorphology seem to be changing gradually especially at "pool" and swing area upstream. After cleaning, turbidity is 95-120NTU which might be accurate actually. Put new SD card in camera.

cals_performed: pH, ORP, DO, Conductivity, Turbidity, Level
visit_comments: Calibrated all including Level since I forgot to calibrate it last time (when Katie gave me the to-do list). High flows. pH and conductivity increasing with increasing Q and stage.

photos_downloaded: SD card collected + field pics taken
visit_comments: Cleaned, log failed to upload repeatedly but finally worked. Replaced SD card but camera started malfunctioning so I pulled it. Probably out of new batteries so will get more and redeploy camera soon.

Upgraded VuLink Cellular, high flows, live readings looked good. DO was NOT calibrated because it would not stabilize. Sensor was super clean. Added more tape because I thought the Sonde wouldn't go down because it was getting stuck by tape. 10 NTU calib was close to 10, but 100 NTU didn't even register the liquid and read 50 NTU. Had trouble with the test upload at first, but works now.

Put new battery in VuLink battery levels are at 99% now. Live readings looked good, I rinsed sensor to get sediment off. It took me a minute to get sonde back in housing, once I openend up the door in the housing, which was about a foot underwater I was able to get the sonde back in the housing. Broke the cleaning rod while trying to get it in the housing, housing got sort of cleaned. However while I was there the end of the housing which gets locked up by the pad lock specifacly the yellow piece is on the housing but can easly come loose if you pull it. This could need fixing in order to ensure security of sonde. Lastly I changed out the SD cards and taped a new project sign on the camera

Similar issue with Legacy where log was running but had only recorded three data points in a 24 hour period. Cleared old logs and started a new log with 1 min recording and 5 min upload, worked properly and data was uploading. Came back and re set log to 15 min record and 3 hour upload. Test upload worked properly and left. Never removed sonde from housing

RDO would not stabilize (temp would), but the numbers in the post live reading looked okay. Sonde was ridiculously difficult to get out. It seemed like there was a lot of sediment caked up inside of the PVC that I could access via the hatch making it hard to yank up, but the flows were also super high making the hatch halfway up my arm. Depth 3ft ish. For RDO, I restored calibration defaults, but it didn't seem to work.

No calibrations, checking on wiper (rectangle conductivity data...it seems like the wiper was stopping on the turbidity sensor which was messing it up) and RDO (not stabilizing…again). Live readings looked good bc calibrated recently. Water had gone down! The InSitu guy (John) didn't know what was up w the wiper and is starting an email correspondance with me currently. Our intermediate solution was to remove the wiper to see if that is fixing the problem. For RDO, I did everything possible: calibration default restore, factory reset, more grease, wiped down the housing, new RDO cap (ended up sticking with the old one). Another InSitu representative told me to send in the sensor, so that might need to happen. Even after all of this, RDO would not stabilize. So, I put it back in the water.

I reglued the top cover for the housing, it is securely attached to the housing now. VuLink got a new software update, which auto pauses the log while you are connected. Started a new log and downloaded the old log which ran from 2023-06-26 12:52:46 till 2023-06-27 09:27:24. Lastly, the water level was significantly lower than the last time I was there on 2023-06-13

Took photos for John and troubleshot the odd conductivity problem where data looks like it's being impacted by the brush. We removed all the sensors only to find that the wiper port looked fine. Chloe **GENTLY** tried to bend it to a more upright position (but it didn't really work all that well). Afterwards, we put back on the wiper. There was a thin but sturdy layer of sediment on the sensors that didn't easily come off in water, we used a cloth. Huge crawdad find! Turbidity in pre live looked off at 36NTU, post was around 8. Cleaned housing.

Change SD card and batteries. Live treadings showed conductivity at 757 (no sensor malfunction...I checked in standard solution), and despite RDO sensor being wacky, the RDO was sitting at 93%/6.73. Depth at 1.91ft. Removed all sensors to try and see if there was a bend to fix the wiper-conductivity (box data) issue. There was a slight bend but I couldn't fix it with my bare hands (SUPER slight bend). I found I could push the wiper cylinder down within the wiper port so I tried that. Then the wiper was put back on but made a terrible clicking noise and was being stopped on conductivity. InSitu told me there was a bend and that I may need to switch it or send it into them.
Cleaned senors, the live readings looked good. depth was showing negative 3.4 howver the when I looked at the log it was about a foot deep. took wiper off and replaced it with the wiper port plug.

Live readings looked good, however the turbidty was high in the upper 100s range. After I cleaned the sensors the all the data on the livereadings looked great turbidty was at 17NTU. Conductivity was pretty hiugh in mid 700s. cleaned the housing with the brush and took pictures of the housing. VuLink battery was 30%

Cleaned sonde (no wiper caused a light layer of filmy sediment on the sensors), turbidity readings were getting high. Used towel to get off filmy layer as well. Installed an entirely new wiper port, and the wiper worked perfectely. After putting back in, turbidity was back down to normal values around 7NTU.
Log was running when connected?? So I paused it. Changed batteries, successful test upload. SD card replaced, camera batteries were at 57%.

crew: Chloe Miller, Juan De La Torre
visit_comments: Pre live looked okay besides RDO (6.8, 68%) and depth (-3ft -- previews said 2.3ft). There was some sediment on restrictor but not very much on sensors. Didn't calib ORP at first so we swung by at the end to do it really quickly (est 2:00 mst?)…forgot bottle and realized it was in the car. RDO doesn't work still, go figure. Post live looked good, RDO was back to reading normal numbers in 90%s.

crew: Juan De La Torre, Sam Struthers
visit_comments: Switched housing from 2 inches to 4 inches. Sensor was out from 9:30 to 12:45. RDO sensor did not stabilize. In Situ folks came out to record us calibrate the sensor and replace the housing.
Connected cu at500 with splitter and redeployed with them connected together

Just went to timberline to finish up turbidity, wasn't calibrated last time I was there. additionally changed the camera mode from timelapse to pir photo. because the sd card had videos on it instead of pictures

crew: Sam Struthers, Juan De La Torre
visit_comments: Pulled sonde while spray painting housing, cleaned sensor and replaced wiper for one in better condition

Camera was there! However, it was on the movement only setting, so I had to change it back to timelapse as it only had 60 photos or so on there since last time. Batteries were at 50%. The sonde was good, nothing too odd for live readings. I cleaned the CU sonde as well. They were a little biofilmy, but not too much. RDO seemed to be jumping around a bit, but hopefully that's fixed now. Depth at 2.2ft.
